  "prompt": "How much sugar is good for health?",
  "response": "The amount of sugar that is considered \"good\" or acceptable for health depends on various factors, including individual dietary needs, overall health, and activity level. However, major health organizations provide general guidelines for sugar consumption:\n\n1. **World Health Organization (WHO):** The WHO recommends reducing the intake of free sugars to less than 10% of total daily energy intake. For additional health benefits, they suggest reducing it to below 5%. For an average adult, this translates to about 25 grams (6 teaspoons) of sugar per day.\n\n2. **American Heart Association (AHA):** The AHA advises that women limit their intake of added sugars to no more than 100 calories per day (about 25 grams or 6 teaspoons), and men limit theirs to 150 calories per day (about 37.5 grams or 9 teaspoons).\n\n\"Free sugars\" or \"added sugars\" include sugars added to foods and drinks, as well as sugars naturally present in honey, syrups, fruit juices, and fruit juice concentrates. These recommendations do not apply to sugars naturally found in fruits, vegetables, or dairy products, as those are typically accompanied by essential nutrients.\n\nIt's important to monitor sugar consumption because excessive intake of added sugars is linked to a greater risk of obesity, type 2 diabetes, heart disease, and other health issues. Reducing sugar intake and choosing a diet rich in whole foods like fruits, vegetables, and whole grains can promote better overall health.\n\nRemember that everyone's nutritional needs can be different, so it's a good idea to consult with a healthcare provider or a registered dietitian for personalized advice.",
